The course describes the development of the societal and political order and the mentality and wold-view of the Ancient Greek civilisation during the Early Iron Age, the Archaic and the Classical period (ca 1200-320 BC).Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course describes the development of the societal and political order and the mentality and wold-view of the Ancient Greek civilisation during the Early Iron Age, the Archaic and the Classical period (ca 1200-320 BC). It discusses these aspects of the development in their organic connectedness, showing the Greek civilisation, on the one hand, as a part of the Ancient Near Eastern and Mediterranean 'world system', while on the other hand revealing its specific characteristics and originality in this historical and cultural context. The course doesn't present one firm concept of development, but discusses different views concerning this set of problems.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  - The student can describe the main character of the Ancient Greek civilisation, both the characteristics shared by other Ancient Near Eastern and Mediterranean societies and cultures, and the originality of the Greek achievements on this background. - The student knows and is able to describe the main problems and points of discussion concerning the emergence and development of the Greek civilisation, the principal sources on which the discussion is based, and the principal solutions proposed by the modern research. - The student understands different points of views concerning the societal, political and cultural development of the Greek civilisation.
